Pages = {201-238},
Month = {MAY 8},
Abstract = {The zeylanica group is one of the six species groups of the anthophilic
   genus Colocasiomyia de Meijere in the family Drosophilidae. In addition
   to two known species, five morphospecies have been recognized as members
   of this species group but left undescribed formally. In this study,
   species delimitation of these putatively new species was determined by
   barcoding of the mitochondrial COI (cytochrome c oxydase subunit I) gene
   and morphological comparison. Phylogenetic relationships within the
   genus Colocasiomyia were inferred by a cladistic analysis of 89
   morphological characters. Based on the results of these analyses, we
   redefined the zeylanica species group and established two subgroups
   within it: the zeylanica subgroup comprised of C. zeylanica, C.
   nepalensis, C. pinangae sp. nov., C. besaris sp. nov. and C. luciphila
   sp. nov., and the oligochaeta subgroup of C. oligochaeta sp. nov. and C.
   grimaldii sp. nov. In addition, we briefly address the anthophilic
   habits of drosophilid flies using palm (Arecaceae) inflorescences,
   especially of the zeylanica group, scattered collection records from the
   Oriental and},
